2 What are the variables related to high salary of players?

As the dataset is related to the income or value of a player, so the first question we care about is what makes their income so different. Basing on the variables in the data, we propose following:

2.1 position

Position is the most intuitively reason we would associate with income there are positions more important in a game, they are supposed to make more money.

2.1.1 Average highest

I take the average over the annual salary after grouping them by position. If we look at the number of positions by unique(), we see there are 24 positions, but we are concentrating on the highest ones, so I keep the top 10 average salary positions to display in the plot. Red dot in the plot identifies the average value.
Though the boxes are scaled by large value outliers, we cannot remove those outliers, because they represent the extraordinarily high paid players in each position, well take care of them later, Now I will zoom in to show the tendency, of these average values.

If we look at this zoomed in plot, we find the avarage annual salary of quarterback is getting close to 6 million, which could be twice of the number of 4-3 outside linebacker, but there are still 14 positions not showed here, so quarterback is indeed a highly-paid position.

If we take a closer look at the boxplot, we find all the medians are close to the bottom of the box and much lower than the red dots, which means high-paid players extensively raise the mean value, so we would like to look at those extraordinarily high paid players, i.e.the outliers mentioned before.

2.1.2 Top highest in each position

Here we extract top 10 highest paid players in top 10 high-paid positions, and plot the average annual salary versus position,

This plots shows that even in the most-paid subset, quarterback has the obvious highest yearly pay. If we look at the overall trend of each position, they follow a similar trend we had in the previous box plot.

2.2 age

Another factor matters to salary could be age. It is conceivable that a player at younger age tend to be more energetic and active while older players are more experience at team-work and techniques, so there could be an optimum age preferred by clubs and willing to pay more.

2.2.1 Top player age distribution

To look at if age affect salary, we will first look at the most paid players in each position to see their age distribution.

This plot has bin width of 2, and the red dashed line marks the mean of the distribution. We found most top-paid players have age between 25 and 31, and the mean is 29, very few of them are over 40, so this distribution is slightly right-skewed.

2.2.1 All players age distribution

We also interested in age distribution of all players, so we plot this:

The overall age distribution has a similar tendency to the top-paid one: right tail, but much heavy this time. This reflects that younger players are preferred in this game. Another evidence verifies younger preference is the mean, in this plot, the mean decreases to 26, which was 19 in the previous plot. This young-age preference is understandable, because aging and experience dont guarantee for good performance.

2.3 team

Just like some companies are willing to pay more to their employees, annual salary can vary by teams.

2.3.1 Average salary versus team

We take average of each team and plot the following: As what happened in position, there are outliers in each team. There seems a fluctuation, zoom in to identify the tendency.

Unlike the position, there is not an outstanding best-paid team, rather, there are few less-paid teams, so lets look at the bar plot.

In this bar plot, we can see the average annual of each team fluctuates between 2 million and 2.5 million without outstanding high value. But there are two teams: Dolphins, Ravens are obviously have lower values than the other teams. We know that headquarter is the position to have higher salary, so we want to know if these teams are paying lower salary depends on positions.

Here we plot the average annual salary distributions by positions. To compare the how are the position investing strategy of Dolphins and Ravens are different from the overall trend, we put the plots together.

These three plots are different in their own way, but one noteworthy position is Safty. Both Dolphins and Ravens are willing to pay a lot to this position. But if we look at the top most plot, thats not the case. Its probably that these two teams have good defense performance in the games.
